We have that $\frac{3}{5} + \frac{4}{5}i = \cos \alpha + i \sin \alpha$ and $-\frac{12}{13} + \frac{5}{13}i = \cos \beta + i \sin \beta.$ Therefore, $\cos \alpha = \frac{3}{5}$ and $\sin \alpha = \frac{4}{5},$ and $\cos \beta = -\frac{12}{13}$ and $\sin \beta = \frac{5}{13}.$

Then, we have \begin{align*}
\cos (\alpha - \beta) &= \cos \alpha \cos \beta + \sin \alpha \sin \beta \\
&= \frac{3}{5} \cdot \left(-\frac{12}{13}\right) + \frac{4}{5} \cdot \frac{5}{13} \\
&= \boxed{-\frac{24}{65}}.
\end{align*}
